AST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Soules","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Soule  .","French (<b>Soulès</b>): plural form of <b>Soulé</b> (see   Soule  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Soule","meanings":["English (Gloucestershire): of Norman origin, a variant of   Soul  .","French (<b>Soulé</b>): topographic name for someone who lived in a house exposed to sun, a variant of   Soulier   2; or a habitational name from Soulé, the name of several places in the southwestern part of France.","History: George Soule (1600–80), one of the passengers on the <i>Mayflower</i> in 1620, was one of the founders of Duxbury, MA, where he became comparatively wealthy. He left eight children."]},{"name":"Sowles","meanings":["English: variant of   Soules  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. William De Soules was born about 1106, in Roxburghshire, Scotland. She had at least 1 son with William de Soules. She died in Roxburghshire, Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1106–":"umbes 1106–Surnud","1100–1170":"1100–1170","1150–1207":"1150–1207","1106–Female":"1106–Surnud","1106":"1106","Abt 1150":"umbes 1150","about 1106":"umbes 1106","1100":"1100","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","1207":"1207","Liddel Castle, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Roxburghshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Liddesdale, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Liddisdale, Roxburghshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Roxburghshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"about 1106–":"noin 1106–Kuollut","1100–1170":"1100–1170","1150–1207":"1150–1207","1106–Female":"1106–Kuollut","1106":"1106","Abt 1150":"noin 1150","about 1106":"noin 1106","1100":"1100","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","1207":"1207","Liddel Castle, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Roxburghshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Liddesdale, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Liddisdale, Roxburghshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Roxburghshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"about 1106–":"environ 1106–Décédée","1100–1170":"1100–1170","1150–1207":"1150–1207","1106–Female":"1106–Décédée","1106":"1106","Abt 1150":"environ 1150","about 1106":"environ 1106","1100":"1100","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","1207":"1207","Liddel Castle, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Roxburghshire, Écosse, Royaume-Uni","Liddesdale, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Liddisdale, Roxburghshire, Écosse, Royaume-Uni","Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Roxburghshire, Écosse","lifeSummary":"Mrs. William De Soules est née environ 1106, à Roxburghshire, Écosse. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec William de Soules. Elle est d